        "The bottom row charts the distribution of insurance costs associated with these line items.\n",
        "\n",
        "* Distribution (Histogram): Similar to Unit Price, the insurance costs are heavily right-skewed. The highest density of records falls under the 1,000 USD mark, with over 7,000 counts in the primary bin. However, unlike Unit Price, the \"tail\" of this distribution is much \"fatter,\" showing a gradual decay in frequency as costs increase toward 3,000â€“4,000 USD.\n",
        "\n",
        "* Outliers (Boxplot): The boxplot shows a very dense \"cluster\" of outliers starting around 500 USD and extending continuously to 4,000 USD. There are also distinct extreme outliers appearing near the 5,000 USD and 6,000 USD marks. The green box (interquartile range) is very narrow and positioned at the far left, suggesting that 50% of the data lives within a very small, low-cost range."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Nqcm6ALdTPOE"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "from scipy.stats import skew, kurtosis\n",
        "\n",
        "def get_distribution_metrics(df: pd.DataFrame):\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "    Analyzes numerical columns and returns a formatted\n",
        "    summary of skewness and kurtosis.\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "    # 1. Isolate numerical columns\n",
        "    numeric_df = df.select_dtypes(include=['int64', 'float64'])\n",
        "\n",
        "    if numeric_df.empty:\n",
        "        print(\"âš ï¸ No numerical columns found in the DataFrame.\")\n",
        "        return None\n",
        "\n",
        "    # 2. Calculate metrics\n",
        "    # We use fisher=False for Pearsonâ€™s definition (Normal Distribution = 3)\n",
        "    # Use fisher=True (default) if you want Excess Kurtosis (Normal Distribution = 0)\n",
        "    metrics = {\n",
        "        'Skewness': numeric_df.apply(lambda x: skew(x.dropna())),\n",
        "        'Kurtosis': numeric_df.apply(lambda x: kurtosis(x.dropna(), fisher=False))\n",
        "    }\n",
        "\n",
        "    # 3. Create a summary table\n",
        "    summary_table = pd.DataFrame(metrics)\n",
        "\n",
        "    # 4. Add \"Interpretations\" for better UX\n",
        "    summary_table['Skew Type'] = summary_table['Skewness'].apply(\n",
        "        lambda x: 'Positive' if x > 0.5 else ('Negative' if x < -0.5 else 'Symmetric')\n",
        "    )\n",
        "\n",
        "    print(\"\\n--- ðŸ“Š Statistical Distribution Summary ---\")\n",
        "    print(summary_table.to_string())\n",
        "\n",
        "    return summary_table\n",
        "\n",
        "# Execution\n",
        "# Assuming fed_df is your pre-defined DataFrame\n",
        "stats_summary = get_distribution_metrics(fed_df)"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "xxE3SouGEszy"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**Skewness and Kurtosisâ€”to understand data's distribution. **\n",
        "\n",
        "The results were revealing: variables like Unit Price and Weight showed extreme Positive Skewness and Leptokurtic Kurtosis. This tells us that our shipping operations are dominated by a standard 'norm,' but we are subject to extreme outliers that significantly impact freight costs and insurance values. Understanding these tails is crucial for building robust predictive models, as standard linear regressions might be skewed by these non-normal distributions.\"\n",
        "\n",
        "The values confirm the above conclusions drawn!!!"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "k2Be16_KFBmG"
      }
