    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## Analysis of Top 20 Delivery Frequencies\n",
        "\n",
        "The output shows the number of shipments corresponding to a specific delivery status, where the index is the delay (in days):\n",
        "\n",
        "* **Negative Index:** Days late (a logistical failure).\n",
        "* **Zero Index:** On-time delivery (success).\n",
        "* **Positive Index:** Days early (a scheduling over-estimation).\n",
        "\n",
        "| Delay Status (Days) | Frequency (Count) | Logistical Significance |\n",
        "| :---: | :---: | :--- |\n",
        "| **-1** | $\\approx \\mathbf{712}$ | **Most Frequent Late Status** (Highest volume of failure). |\n",
        "| **0** | $\\approx \\mathbf{632}$ | **Most Frequent Status Overall** (On-Time performance). |\n",
        "| **-2, -3** | $\\approx \\mathbf{177}$ each | Major contributors to minor delays. |\n",
        "| **+6** | $\\approx \\mathbf{85}$ | Most common **early delivery** (Scheduling buffer). |\n",
        "| **...** | ... | ... |\n",
        "\n",
        "### 1. The Core Operational Failure: Minor Delays\n",
        "\n",
        "The analysis reveals that the supply chain is fundamentally challenged by minor failures:\n",
        "\n",
        "* **$1$ Day is the Top Problem:** The **$1$ day late** status ($\\approx 712$ shipments) is the single most common delivery outcome, surpassing the on-time $0$ day status ($\\approx 632$ shipments). This indicates a systemic tendency for the process to fall short of the schedule by a minimal margin.\n",
        "* **Focus Area:** The vast majority of delivery failures ($1$, $2$, and $3$ days late) are concentrated in the first few days. Fixing the root causes of these minor delaysâ€”likely related to **last-mile logistics**, **documentation hiccups**, or **minor customs issues**â€”would drastically improve overall on-time delivery performance.\n",
        "\n",
        "### 2. Schedule Buffer and Predictability\n",
        "\n",
        "* **Common Early Status:** The visibility of frequent early statuses, such as **$-6$ days early**, indicates that the scheduled delivery dates for many shipments include a significant buffer. This practice ensures delivery success but suggests the **forecasting is conservative**, which can tie up inventory unnecessarily.\n",
        "* **Implication:** For shipments that are frequently early, the logistics team can investigate reducing the scheduled lead time, thereby **improving reporting accuracy** and potentially **reducing inventory holding costs** at the destination."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "0knFATL5uUgR"
      }
