        "## Time Series Analysis: Performance Segregated by Shipment Mode\n",
        "\n",
        "This analysis isolates the trends of **volume (Total Items Shipped)** and **logistical risk (Delayed Deliveries)** for each major shipment method over time.\n",
        "\n",
        "### 1. Total Items Shipped Over Time by Shipment Mode\n",
        "\n",
        "This chart (left image) reveals the **scale and consistency** of volume distribution across different shipment methods.\n",
        "\n",
        "* **Dominance of Air Freight (and Express):** The highest peaks and overall largest cumulative volume belong to the fastest modes (likely **Air** ) and or **Truck**.\n",
        "\n",
        "* **Volume Consistency:** Some modes show a **more stable baseline volume** (lines near the bottom), suggesting they handle routine, non-urgent, or smaller-scale operations that are less impacted by major procurement cycles.\n",
        "\n",
        "* **Air Charter (Sporadic Demand):** This mode appears to begin serious operation around 2009 and exhibits highly sporadic, high-magnitude peaks poast 2012.  The business relied on air and air charther heavily around 2012 on it for consistent, baseline volume is not consistent here.\n",
        "\n",
        "* **Ocean Freight (Defined Project Period):** Ocean volume also appears to start around 2009 picked up between mid of 2010 and then largely cease around 2012. This short, concentrated lifecycle. Its discontinuation post this period requires further analysis\n",
        "\n",
        "### 2. Delayed Deliveries Over Time by Shipment Mode\n",
        "\n",
        "This chart (right image) is a direct measure of **operational failure** or **logistical strain** for each method.\n",
        "\n",
        "* **Air/Express as the Primary Risk Driver:** The line(s) corresponding to the high-volume modes (Air/Truck) show the **highest and most frequent spikes in delays**.\n",
        "* **Systemic Failure:** The most extreme delay peaks (like the one around **2009** or **2012**) often show **multiple shipment modes spiking simultaneously**. This indicates that the failure is **systemic**â€”likely related to customs backlogs, general strikes, port congestion, or a major supply chain disruption that affects all modes simultaneously.\n",
        "* **High-Volume, Low-Delay Modes:** If any mode handles significant volume (Plot 1) but maintains a **flat, low delay rate** (Plot 2), it represents the **most robust and reliable** shipment method. Management should study this mode's processes to improve others.\n",
        "* **Low-Volume, High-Delay Modes:** If a low-volume mode frequently spikes in delays, it indicates an **inefficient process** or a severe bottleneck isolated to that specific transport channel (e.g., a single problematic cross-border route for road transport).\n",
        "\n"
