      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**Analysis of Shipment Volume by Product Sub-Classification**\n",
        "This is a highly granular view of the logistics strategy at the product component level.\n",
        "\n",
        "Lets discuss - the volume distribution, highlighting the differences between the major health commodities (ARV/HRDT) and the remaining groups. It indicates infrequent shipments of large quantities of antiretrovirals, HIV test kits and other essential suppliesâ€”**\n",
        "\n",
        "## Analysis of Shipment Volume by Product Sub-Classification\n",
        "\n",
        "The charts provide a detailed view of how volume is distributed across specific drug formulations (Sub-Classifications) and which transport modes support that volume.\n",
        "\n",
        "### 1. ARV & HRDT Product Groups (Left Chart)\n",
        "\n",
        "This chart, focusing on the high-volume medical commodities, demonstrates show a **mixed logistical approach** with an overwhelming reliance on **Air Freight** for mass distribution.\n",
        "\n",
        "* **Volume Dominance:** The largest volume bar belongs to one of the **ARV Sub-Classifications**, likely representing the primary or most common treatment regimen. This specific sub-group drives the entire volume of the ARV product line.\n",
        "* **Air Freight Monopoly:**: For **every single sub-classification** within both ARV and HRDT, **Air Freight (Standard Air)** is the mode responsible for moving the vast majority of drugs. The bars for other modes (e.g., Express) are almost invisible in comparison to the Air bar.\n",
        "    * *Operational Insight:* This pattern confirms that the priority for these essential drugs is **speed and maintaining the cold chain/integrity**, irrespective of the specific formulation. **Air is the default, standard, and primary logistical solution** for all forms of ARV and HRDT.\n",
        "* **HRDT Sub-Classification:** HRDT shows lower overall volume than the primary ARV sub-groups, confirming its more stable, maintenance-level demand. The reliance on Air is absolute.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### 2. Other Product Groups (Right Chart)\n",
        "\n",
        "This chart reveals the logistical strategies for the lower-volume, non-ARV/HRDT products (ACT, ANTM, MRDT), showing a complete reliance on Air solution probably due to the significance of speedy delivery and urgency of treatment for malaria .\n",
        "\n",
        "* **Highest Volume Sub-Group:** The most prominent group here is an **ANTM Sub-Classification**. While its total volume is significantly lower than the dominant ARV sub-group (left chart), it is the largest driver among these secondary products.\n",
        "\n",
        "* **Cost-Effective Strategy for ARV:** The ARV sub-groups show the **greatest balance** between different modes. They have meaningful contributions from **Road freight** and possibly other modes like **Ocean (if present)**. This re-emphasizes that ACT, being a malaria treatment often stocked in high volumes in endemic areas, prioritizes **cost and bulk capacity** over the absolute speed required for ARV.\n",
        "* **MRDT (Low Volume):** The MRDT sub-groups show very **low total volume** across all modes, reinforcing its position as a specialized or low-demand item. It still utilizes Air and Express, suggesting that when it is needed, it is typically an urgent, low-batch shipment.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Key Conclusion\n",
        "\n",
        "The organization's logistics strategy is strictly **product-hierarchy driven**:\n",
        "\n",
        "1.  **Life-Saving, High-Volume (ARV/HRDT):** **Speed is non-negotiable**. All sub-classifications are shipped almost exclusively via **Air**.\n",
        "2.  **Other Commodities (ACT/ANTM):** **Cost is a factor**. Logistical modes are diversified, using **Road** and **Express** strategically alongside Air to manage costs while meeting varied service requirements."
