      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "  \n",
        "  * **A simple Bar Chart**(or Column Chart) is used to compare the magnitude of individual, independent categories.\n",
        "\n",
        "  * **The Bubble Chart**(Chart 2 in your code) was chosen for the plot of Shipment Volume vs. Delay Rate because it is the ideal visualization for analyzing the relationship between three numerical dimensions simultaneously with Bubble Size (Area): Total Shipments (Volume) - reinforcing the X-axis.\n",
        "\n",
        "  * **Pie Chart:** Proportions and Distribution (The \"How Much of the Whole\")**:The pie chart is visually effective when the primary goal is to show how different categories contribute to a single whole (100%).\n",
        "\n",
        "  * **Performance Distribution Bar Chart (Chart 5)** Primary reason for creating Performance Distribution Bar Chart (Chart 5)  is to provide a high-level summary of the overall logistical health of destination markets. It answers the question: \"How is the entire portfolio of countries performing, and where is the majority of our risk concentrated?\n",
        "    * The number of countries in the 'Poor' (Red) category dictates the size of the emergency task force needed.\n",
        "\n",
        "    * The number of countries in the 'Excellent' (Green) category indicates the number of potential regions available for new business initiatives or benchmarking.\n",
        "\n",
        "  * **The Cumulative Delay Analysis plot** (Chart 6) is a powerful strategic tool, often referred to as a Pareto Curve (or related to a Lorenz Curve in economics).It is generated specifically to apply the 80/20 Rule to the problem of shipment delays and answers the critical business question: \"Which few countries are responsible for the majority of our total delay volume?\""
      ],
