        "  *Internal Date Progression:* Scheduled Delivery Date is highly correlated with Delivered to Client Date ($\\mathbf{+0.59}$), which, in turn, is highly correlated with Delivery Recorded Date ($\\mathbf{+0.82}$). This confirms a standard, sequential flow through the delivery stages.\n",
        "\n",
        "2. **Logistical Choices and Time**:\n",
        "  *Cost and Weight:* As expected, Freight Cost (USD) shows a very strong positive correlation with Weight (Kilograms) ($\\mathbf{+0.65}$). This confirms that shipment weight is the single most significant physical driver of freight cost in your system.\n",
        "\n",
        "  * *Cost and First Line Designation (Negative): * *Freight Cost (USD) has a strong negative correlation ($\\mathbf{-0.68}$) with First Line Designation. This is an unusual and important finding:It suggests that shipments with the First Line Designation (often associated with high-priority or urgent products) are somehow associated with lower overall freight costs. This needs investigation, perhaps because these shipments utilize special, pre-negotiated contracts or government-provided transport.\n",
        "\n",
        "3. **Product Group and Volume/Dosage:** Product Group is moderately to highly correlated with both Dosage ($\\mathbf{+0.60}$) and Dosage Form ($\\mathbf{+0.58}$). This confirms that the type of product (e.g., ARV, HRDT) heavily determines the standard pill count and format, which affects packaging and shipment volume.\n"
